The '''Jordan national football team''' ({{langx|ar|منتخب الأردن لكرة القدم}}), nicknamed '''''Al Nashama''''' ({{lit|''The Chivalrous Ones''}}), represents [[Jordan]] in men's international [[Association football|football]]. It is under the jurisdiction of the [[Jordan Football Association]]. 

Jordan has played in five [[AFC Asian Cup]] tournaments, appearing in the final of a major tournament for the first time in the [[2023 AFC Asian Cup|2023]] edition, finishing as runners-up. They also finished runners-up of the [[FIFA Arab Cup]] in [[2025 FIFA Arab Cup|2025]], and have won the [[Arab Games]] twice, in [[1997 Arab Games|1997]] and [[1999 Arab Games|1999]]. The team reached the [[WAFF Championship]] final on three occasions but never won it. The country qualified for their first [[FIFA World Cup]] in [[2026 FIFA World Cup|2026]].

==History==
{{Expand section|date=June 2025}}
=== Early history (1953–1996) ===
The Jordanian national football team's first international match was played in 1953 in [[Egypt]] where the team were defeated by Syria 3–1. The first [[FIFA World Cup]] qualifiers Jordan took part in were for the [[1986 FIFA World Cup qualification|1986 tournament]]. They failed to qualify for the World Cup in 1986.

=== Development era (1997–2007) ===
{{Expand section|date=June 2025}}
{{Cite section|date=June 2025}}
[[Mohammad Awad]] coached Jordan to two [[Arab Games]] championships, in 1997 in [[Beirut]], and 1999 in [[Amman]].  The country then hired [[Serbia]]n head coach [[Branko Smiljanić]], who won two matches in the first round of [[2002 FIFA World Cup qualification|2002 World Cup qualifiers]]. Jordan failed to qualify for the next round. Jordan also reached the semi-finals of the [[2002 Arab Cup]].<ref>{{Cite web |title=Arabian Cup 2002 Details |url=https://www.rsssf.org/tablesa/arabcup02-details.html?utm |access-date=2025-09-21 |website=www.rsssf.org}}</ref>

Under the leadership of Egyptian [[Mahmoud El-Gohary]], the Jordan national team was able to qualify for their first [[AFC Asian Cup]] tournament, in [[2004 AFC Asian Cup|2004]], and reach the quarter-finals, where they lost to eventual winners [[Japan national football team|Japan]] in a penalty shoot-out. Despite this, Jordan reached their highest-ever [[FIFA World Rankings|FIFA world ranking]], at 37th place; they would eventually fail to qualify for the [[2006 FIFA World Cup]] in Germany.

In the 2004 and 2007 WAFF Championships, Jordan finished in third place in the former and made another semi-final in the latter. Five matches into [[2007 AFC Asian Cup qualification]], El-Gohary retired as a football coach, and the [[Jordan Football Association]] hired the Portuguese [[Nelo Vingada]] to take over as the head coach of Jordan; they still missed the [[2007 AFC Asian Cup|finals]].

=== Renaissance of Jordan football (2008–2015) ===
Under Vingada, Jordan were runners-up in the [[2008 West Asian Football Federation Championship]], but failed to qualify for the [[2010 FIFA World Cup|2010 World Cup]] in South Africa. He was replaced by Iraq's [[Adnan Hamad]], a coach in Asia known for his successes with his national team in Iraq as head coach as well as Iraq U-23 and other Iraq youth teams and clubs.{{CN|date=June 2025}} Jordan qualified for their second Asian Cup tournament in [[2011 AFC Asian Cup|2011]], where they made the quarter-finals before losing to [[Uzbekistan national football team|Uzbekistan]] 2–1. Jordan also finished runner-up at the [[2011 Arab Games]] in Qatar. In 2013, Jordan ended up third in their qualifying group for the [[2014 FIFA World Cup|World Cup]] the following year. 

Another Egyptian, [[Hossam Hassan (footballer, born 1966)|Hossam Hassan]], led Jordan to the play-off against Uzbekistan to determine the AFC participant in the [[2014 FIFA World Cup qualification (inter-confederation play-offs)|inter-confederation play-offs]]. With the two teams still evenly matched at full-time in the second leg, Jordan eventually progressed to the intercontinental playoff after winning 9–8 on penalties. The Jordanians missed their first FIFA World Cup debut after losing 5–0 on aggregate to [[Uruguay national football team|Uruguay]]. 

Jordan qualified to the [[2015 AFC Asian Cup]]. On 3 September 2014, [[Ray Wilkins]] was appointed as the new head coach. Wilkins led Jordan to a group stage exit at the Asian Cup after losses to Iraq and [[Japan national football team|Japan]] and a win over [[Palestine national football team|Palestine]].

=== Stagnation (2016–2023) ===
Jordan failed to make the final round of [[2018 FIFA World Cup qualification (AFC)|2018 FIFA World Cup qualification]], losing 0–1 to [[Kyrgyzstan national football team|Kyrgyzstan]] and 1–5 to [[Australia men's national soccer team|Australia]]. They would qualify for the [[2019 AFC Asian Cup|2019 Asian Cup]] where Jordan defeated Australia 1–0 and [[Syria national football team|Syria]] 2–0, along with a draw against Palestine in the group stage. They were knocked out by [[Vietnam national football team|Vietnam]], losing in a penalty shootout 2–4.

In the [[2022 FIFA World Cup qualification – AFC second round|2022 World Cup qualification second round]], Jordan finished third in their group. Subsequently, they clinched the top spot in their group during the [[2023 AFC Asian Cup qualification – third round|2023 Asian Cup qualification]], earning themselves a berth in the main tournament.

=== Re-emergence (2024–present) ===
[[File:Asian Nations Cup - Jordan and South Korea (67).jpg|thumb|243x243px|Jordan's starting 11 against South Korea in the 2023 Asian Cup]]

In June 2023, [[Hussein Ammouta]] was appointed as the Jordan national team coach.<ref>{{Cite web |title=Ammouta takes charge of Jordan |url=https://www.the-afc.com/en/national/afc_asian_cup/news/ammouta_takes_charge_of_jordan.html |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240116171537/https://www.the-afc.com/en/national/afc_asian_cup/news/ammouta_takes_charge_of_jordan.html |archive-date=16 January 2024 |access-date=2024-01-16 |website=the-AFC |language=en}}</ref> In early 2024, he led his squad to their first ever [[2023 AFC Asian Cup final|Asian Cup final]], after defeating Iraq 3–2 after scoring two goals during stoppage time, and beating [[Tajikistan national football team|Tajikistan]] 1–0 and South Korea 2–0 during the knockout stages. In the final, Jordan lost 3–1 to the host nation [[Qatar national football team|Qatar]].<ref>{{cite web |date=10 February 2024 |title=Akram Afif's hat-trick of penalties secures Asian Cup glory for Qatar |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2024/feb/10/qatar-jordan-asian-cup-final-match-report |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240210193719/https://www.theguardian.com/football/2024/feb/10/qatar-jordan-asian-cup-final-match-report |archive-date=10 February 2024 |access-date=10 February 2024 |work=The Guardian}}</ref> Following the national team's historic run to the Asian Cup final, Jordan's [[FIFA Men's World Ranking|FIFA ranking]] rose to 70th, the nation's highest since September 2014.<ref>{{Cite web |title=Men's Ranking |url=https://www.fifa.com/origin1904-p.cxm.fifa.com/fifa-world-ranking/men |access-date=2024-02-15 |website=www.fifa.com |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |title=African and Asian teams grab headlines in latest ranking |url=https://www.fifa.com/fifaplus/en/tournaments/mens/worldcup/canadamexicousa2026/articles/fifa-world-ranking-february-2024 |access-date=2024-02-15 |website=www.fifa.com}}</ref> 

In June 2024, Ammouta requested to leave Jordan due to family reasons and was replaced by [[Jamal Sellami]], who signed a three-year contract.<ref>{{Cite web |date=2024-06-22 |title=تعيين المغربي جمال السلامي مدربا لمنتخب الأردن خلفا لـ عموتة |url=https://www.skynewsarabia.com/sport/1723987-تعيين-المغربي-جمال-السلامي-مدربا-لمنتخب-الأردن |access-date=2024-06-23 |website=Sky News Arabia |language=ar}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |last= |date=June 22, 2024 |title=Jordan parts ways with coach Ammouta by mutual consent |url=https://www.reuters.com/sports/soccer/jordan-parts-ways-with-coach-ammouta-by-mutual-consent-2024-06-22/ |website=Reuters}}</ref> On 5 June 2025, Jordan secured a berth at the [[2026 FIFA World Cup]], their first ever, with a 3–0 away victory over [[Oman national football team|Oman]].<ref>{{cite web |date=5 June 2025 |title=World Cup 2026: Jordan, South Korea, Uzbekistan qualify |url=https://www.espn.com/soccer/story/_/id/45458584/world-cup-2026-qualified-uzbekistan-australia-south-korea-jordan |access-date=5 June 2025 |publisher=ESPN}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |date=6 June 2025 |title=History-making Jordan qualify for first World Cup |url=https://www.fifa.com/en/tournaments/mens/worldcup/canadamexicousa2026/articles/jordan-qualify |accessdate=31 July 2025 |work=FIFA.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |date=11 June 2025 |title=Jordan's long road to World Cup qualification took a strange diversion |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2025/jun/11/jordan-world-cup-qualification-harry-redknapp-ray-wilkins |accessdate=31 July 2025 |work=Guardian}}</ref> 

In December 2025, Sellami led Jordan to their first ever [[2025 FIFA Arab Cup final|FIFA Arab Cup final]]. Jordan went unbeaten up until the final, beating the [[United Arab Emirates national football team|United Arab Emirates]] 2–1, [[Kuwait national football team|Kuwait]] 3–1, [[Egypt national football team|Egypt]] 3–0, Iraq 1–0 and Saudi Arabia 1–0. In the final, Jordan lost 3–2 to [[Morocco national football team|Morocco]].<ref>{{Cite web |date=18 December 2025 |title=Morocco Come From Behind to Defeat Jordan and Win the 2025 FIFA Arab Cup |url=https://www.beinsports.com/en-us/soccer/fifa-arab-cup/articles/morocco-come-from-behind-to-defeat-jordan-and-win-the-2025-fifa-arab-cup-2025-12-18 |website=[[beinSports]]}}</ref> Following the historic run in the Arab Cup, [[Abdullah II of Jordan|His Majesty Abdullah II]] granted Sellami with Jordanian citizenship.<ref>{{Cite web |date=18 December 2025 |title=Nashama coach Jamal Sellami to receive Jordanian citizenship |url=https://en.royanews.tv/news/65826/Jordan-striker-Yazan-Al-Naimat-to-undergo-knee-surgery-in-Doha-on-Wednesday |website=Roya News}}</ref>

== Home stadiums ==
Jordan's primary home stadium is the [[Amman International Stadium]] in [[Amman]], where the national team plays majority of its home matches. The stadium is also home to [[Al-Faisaly SC (Amman)|Al-Faisaly]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.worldstadiums.com/stadium_pictures/middle_east/jordan/amman_stadium.shtml|title=World Stadiums - International Stadium in Amman|website=www.worldstadiums.com|access-date=2010-07-01|archive-date=2010-04-05|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100405132004/http://www.worldstadiums.com/stadium_pictures/middle_east/jordan/amman_stadium.shtml|url-status=dead}}</ref> Other stadiums that Jordan occasionally plays at include [[King Abdullah II Stadium]] in Amman, home to [[Al-Wehdat SC|Al-Wehdat]] and [[Petra Stadium]] in Amman, home to the [[Jordan women's national football team|women's national team]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.fifa.com/u17womensworldcup/destination/cities/city=1913/|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161003072947/http://www.fifa.com/u17womensworldcup/destination/cities/city=1913/|url-status=dead|archive-date=3 October 2016|title = King Abdullah II International Stadium – Amman|access-date=27 November 2021|publisher=FIFA}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.youthcity.gov.jo/petra%20stadium.html |title=Archived copy |access-date=2017-09-21 |archive-date=2017-09-22 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170922050825/http://www.youthcity.gov.jo/petra%20stadium.html |url-status=dead }}</ref>

In late 2025, plans were announced for a new home stadium named Al Hussein bin Abdallah II in the new [[Amra City]] as part of Jordan's new urban and sports development initiatives. Construction is set to start in 2026 and to be completed by 2029.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://jordantimes.com/news/local/king-briefed-on-government-plan-to-develop-first-phase-of-amra-city|title=King briefed on government plan to develop first phase of Amra City|date=2025-12-14|accessdate=2025-12-19|publisher=The Jordan Times|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://jordantimes.com/news/local/govt-to-launch-tenders-for-amra-city-development-project|title=Gov’t to launch tenders for Amra City development project|date=2025-12-14|accessdate=2025-12-19|publisher=The Jordan Times|language=en}}</ref>

